## The RMF as a Cycle

One of the most important things I took from today's reading is that the RMF is explicitly designed as a cycle, not a linear process. The diagram in SP 800-37 shows continuous monitoring feeding back into earlier steps — because monitoring findings may require revisiting categorization if new data types are introduced, reselecting controls if new threats emerge, or reimplementing controls if assessment reveals gaps.
```
+------------------+
|     PREPARE      |
+--------+---------+
         |
         v
+--------+---------+
|    CATEGORIZE    |
+--------+---------+
         |
         v
+--------+---------+
|      SELECT      |
+--------+---------+
         |
         v
+--------+---------+
|    IMPLEMENT     |
+--------+---------+
         |
         v
+--------+---------+
|      ASSESS      |
+--------+---------+
         |
         v
+--------+---------+
|    AUTHORIZE     |
+--------+---------+
         |
         v
+--------+---------+
|     MONITOR      |
+--------+---------+
         |
         +──────────────────────────────────────────┐
                                                    |
         Monitoring findings feed back into         |
         Categorize, Select, and Implement          |
         as the system and threat environment ──────+
         evolve over time
```

That cyclical design reflects a mature understanding of how security actually works. Threats are not static. Systems change. Organizations evolve. A framework that treats authorization as the end state rather than a milestone in an ongoing process will always fall behind the threat environment it is trying to address.

