## Where I Expect the Hardest Work to Be

Having worked through the overview today, here is my honest assessment of where Phase 2 will be most challenging:

**Select Controls** is going to require the most careful thinking. NIST SP 800-53 Revision 5 contains 20 control families and hundreds of individual controls. Selecting the right baseline for OpenMRS — and then tailoring it appropriately for a cloud-hosted, healthcare-focused deployment — requires understanding both the framework and the system in detail. The AWS shared responsibility model adds another layer of complexity, because some controls are partially or fully satisfied by AWS and others remain entirely the customer's responsibility.

**Assess Controls** is where I have the biggest knowledge gap. I understand implementation. I am less clear on what rigorous assessment looks like in practice — the testing methods, the evidence standards, the documentation format. I want to go as deep as I can on this in Phase 2.

**Monitor** is where I expect the most ongoing complexity. Cloud environments change constantly — new services get added, configurations drift, new vulnerabilities are discovered, access patterns shift. Building a continuous monitoring program that is genuinely useful rather than just a compliance artifact feels like one of the hardest practical challenges in the entire framework.

